 "components": {
  "instruction": "Classify the given text into one of these categories: alarm_query, alarm_set, calendar_query, calendar_remove, calendar_set, cooking_recipe, datetime_query, email_query, email_sendemail, general_quirky, iot_hue_lightoff, lists_createoradd, lists_query, lists_remove, music_query, news_query, play_audiobook, play_music, play_podcasts, play_radio, qa_currency, qa_definition, qa_factoid, qa_stock, recommendation_events, recommendation_locations, social_post, takeaway_order, transport_query, weather_query.\n\nImportant distinctions and rules:\n\n1. REMINDERS vs ALARMS: Requests to create reminders (e.g., \"make a reminder for friday at six p.m.\", \"remind me to...\") should be classified as 'calendar_set', NOT 'alarm_set'. The 'alarm_set' category is specifically for setting alarms (e.g., \"set an alarm for 6 am\", \"wake me up at 7\").\n\n2. DISTANCE QUERIES: Questions about distances between locations should be classified as 'qa_factoid' (questions seeking factual geographical information), NOT 'transport_query'. The 'transport_query' category is only for queries about transportation options, routes, schedules, or travel methods (e.g., \"how do I get to the airport\", \"what's the best route to work\", \"when is the next bus\").\n\n3. CONFIRMATION RESPONSES: Short affirmative responses like \"fine\", \"ok\", \"yes\", or similar single-word confirmations in the context of calendar operations should be classified as 'calendar_remove' when they appear to be confirming a removal action.\n\n4. CONTEXT-DEPENDENT CLASSIFICATION: Consider that some inputs may be follow-up responses to previous commands. Single words or brief phrases may represent confirmations or completions of multi-turn interactions.\n\n5. MUSIC ACTION vs MUSIC QUERY: \n   - Use 'play_music' when the user is making a REQUEST or COMMAND to play, add, or queue music (e.g., \"play some jazz\", \"add their first seven albums\", \"i haven't been hearing any king crimson please add their first seven albums\"). Key indicators include action verbs like \"play\", \"add\", \"queue\", \"put on\", or imperative statements about music playback.\n   - Use 'music_query' when the user is ASKING A QUESTION about music or seeking information (e.g., \"what song is this?\", \"who sings this?\", \"what albums does this artist have?\"). Key indicators include question words like \"what\", \"who\", \"when\", \"which\", or interrogative sentence structures.\n   - The presence of words like \"please\" does not make a command into a query - it remains an action request.\n\n6. AUDIO CONTENT DISTINCTIONS:\n   - Use 'play_audiobook' for requests to play audiobooks (books in audio format).\n   - Use 'play_podcasts' for requests to play podcast episodes or podcast series.\n   - Use 'play_radio' for requests to play radio stations, radio shows, or broadcast programs (e.g., \"play for me american idol show\", \"tune into npr\", \"play the morning show\"). This includes named TV/radio programs that are being requested for audio playback.\n   - Use 'play_music' for requests to play songs, albums, or music by artists.\n   - Key distinction: Radio shows and broadcast programs fall under 'play_radio' even if the request doesn't explicitly use the word \"radio\". Look for show names, program names, or broadcast formats.\n\n7. SOCIAL MEDIA ACTIONS: Requests to update, change, or post status updates on social media platforms should be classified as 'social_post'. This includes:\n   - Explicit requests to \"post status\", \"update status\", or \"change status\"\n   - Requests to share content on social media\n   - Commands like \"tweet this\", \"post to facebook\", etc.\n   - Even abbreviated requests like \"change status\" or \"update status\" should be classified as 'social_post', NOT 'general_quirky'\n   - The category 'social_post' covers all social media posting and status update actions\n\n8. GENERAL_QUIRKY: This category should be used for:\n   - Conversational statements or questions that don't fit other categories\n   - Jokes, small talk, or entertainment requests\n   - Questions about the assistant itself\n   - Commands or queries that are ambiguous or don't clearly match any specific domain\n   - Do NOT use this category for social media status updates (those are 'social_post')\n\n9. GENERAL STRATEGY: Analyze the core intent of the user's request. Identify whether they are:\n   - Requesting an action (play, set, send, post, update, etc.)\n   - Querying for information (what, when, who, how much, etc.)\n   - Confirming a previous action\n   Then match the specific domain (music, calendar, social media, transport, etc.) with the action type to arrive at the correct category.\n   \n   Pay special attention to domain-specific keywords:\n   - Status, post, tweet, share → social_post\n   - Play, add music/songs/albums → play_music\n   - Remind, reminder → calendar_set\n   - Alarm, wake → alarm_set"
 },
